erviews Rebecca Gomperts -- tPart VI: Resisting Religious Tyranny -- tIntroduction -- t40. The Dobbs Decision, God, and Moral Conscience -- t41. Open Letter from Seven Muslim American Organizations -- t42. The Torah of Abortion Justice -- t43. What Everyone Gets Wrong about Evangelicals and Abortion -- t44. Abortion and Faith in Florida -- tPart VII: Envisioning the Future -- tIntroduction -- t45. Even with Contraception, People Need and Must Have Access to Abortion -- t46. Building Gender Equity by Engaging Men in Reproductive Responsibility -- t47. Shifting Abortion Public Opinion: A Case Study in Complexity, Compassion, and the Role of Doctors’ Voices -- t48. Rejecting the Abortion Debate Binary Is Essential to Moving toward Reproductive Justice -- t49. Dobbs, Democracy, and Distortion -- t50. The Power of Discernment -- t51. A Black Abortion Provider’s Perspective on Post-Roe America -- t52. Reproductive Justice Futurism: Trust Black Women -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tAbout the Editors -- tAbout the Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA fierce and galvanizing reminder that resistance is everywhere in the fight for abortion and reproductive justice in the United States. Fighting Mad is a book about what ";reproductive justice"; means and what it looks like to fight for it. Editors Krystale E. Littlejohn and Rickie Solinger bring together many of the strongest, most resistant voices in the country to describe the impacts of the Supreme Court's Dobbs decision on abortion access and care. The essayists and change agents gathered in Fighting Mad represent a remarkable breadth of expertise: activists and artists, academics and abortion storytellers, health care professionals and legislators, clinic directors and lawyers, and so many more. They discuss abortion restrictions and strategies to provide care, the impacts of criminalization, efforts to protect the targeted, shortcomings of the past, and visions for the next generation. Fighting Mad captures for the social and historical record the vigorous resistance happening in the early post-Roe moment to show that there are millions on the ground fighting to secure a better future.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aAbortionxLaw and legislationzUnited States. 0aPro-choice movementzUnited States. 0aReproductive rightszUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Abortion & Birth Control.2bisacsh1 aAlspaugh, Amy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAnderson, Wyndi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAyodele Dixon, Ericka, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBhasin, Asees, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBond, Toni, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Jennifer L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCalvasina, Holly, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCano, Gabriela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDesai, Sheila, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFranck, Linda S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrank, Gillian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGelvin, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGutierrez, Cynthia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHafner, Laurinda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHanes, Jenna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarris, Lisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/